    type     = "Education; Robyn Hyperparameters",
    image_q  = "machine learning model optimization parameters",
    hook     = "Robyn ran 3,000 iterations.\n\nAnd still gave the wrong answer.\n\nHere's why hyperparameters matter more than iterations.",
    body     = "When Robyn gives you bad results, it's usually not the data.\n\nIt's the hyperparameter bounds you gave it.\n\nHere's what each one does and why it matters:\n\nTHETA (Adstock Decay)\n→ Range: 0 to 0.8\n→ Controls how long an ad's effect persists\n→ If you set theta too high for a fast-decay channel (e.g. search):\n   The model thinks clicks from 6 weeks ago are still driving conversions today\n→ Fix: Set theta range based on your channel type (search: 0–0.2, TV: 0.3–0.8)\n\nALPHA (Saturation Shape)\n→ Range: 0.5 to 3\n→ Controls whether your response curve is C-shaped or S-shaped\n→ If alpha is too high, Robyn models a steep S-curve\n   Which assumes you need high spend before any returns kick in\n→ Fix: Start with c(0.5, 3) and let Robyn find the shape\n\nGAMMA (Inflection Point)\n→ Range: 0.3 to 1\n→ Controls where diminishing returns start\n→ Lower gamma = earlier diminishing returns\n→ Fix: Set based on your actual spend history relative to typical market rates\n\nTRAIN SIZE\n→ Range: 0.5 to 0.8\n→ What % of data is used for training vs. validation\n→ Too high: model overfits your history, bad at new data\n→ Too low: not enough data to learn patterns\n\nThe practical rule:\n\nBefore you trust Robyn's output, check NRMSE and DECOMP.RSSD.\nIf NRMSE > 0.3 or DECOMP.RSSD is very high; your hyperparameters are wrong.\nStart by widening the bounds and re-running.",
