    body     = "If you don't account for seasonality, your attribution model is a fiction novel.\n\nDuring peak seasons (Black Friday, Cyber Monday, Holidays), conversion rates double. CPCs fluctuate. People are actively looking to spend money.\n\nIf you just look at 'Spend vs. Revenue', the model assumes your ads suddenly became 3x more effective.\n\nRobyn solves this using Prophet to decompose the time series.\nIt breaks your revenue down into three distinct lines:\n\n1. TREND\n→ The long-term trajectory of your business (are you growing year over year?)\n\n2. SEASONALITY\n→ Predictable, repeating patterns (weekly cycles, annual holiday spikes)\n\n3. HOLIDAYS/EVENTS\n→ Specific one-off spikes (e.g., you ran a massive PR campaign or specific discount day)\n\nOnce Robyn strips away the Trend, Seasonality, and Holidays...\nWhat’s left over is the 'residual'.\n\nTHAT is what your marketing actually drove.\n\nBy forcing the model to acknowledge that 'November is just naturally a high-revenue month,' you stop over-crediting your Meta ads just because they happened to be running while people were doing their Christmas shopping.",
